      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why Representation Matters"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A plan is a data structure consumed by an executor. The choice of representation determines whether the executor can exploit parallelism, handle conditional branches, and propagate context between steps. Different representations involve a direct trade-off: "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "richer structure requires more LLM reasoning"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " to generate and more executor complexity to run."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Four plan representations: flat step list, DAG JSON, state machine, hierarchical tree \u2014 each with pros and cons",
          "title": "Plan representation comparison"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Flat Step List"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The simplest representation: a numbered list of tool calls with no dependency metadata. The executor iterates in order, passing prior results forward via placeholders. Suitable for sequential tasks with no parallelism:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from dataclasses import dataclass, field\nfrom typing import Any\n\n@dataclass\nclass FlatStep:\n    index: int\n    tool: str\n    args: dict[str, Any]\n    rationale: str\n\nFLAT_PROMPT = \"\"\"\nReturn a JSON plan as a flat ordered list of steps.\nGoal: {goal}\nTools: {tools}\n\nJSON format: {{\"steps\": [\n  {{\"index\": 1, \"tool\": \"...\", \"args\": {{...}}, \"rationale\": \"...\"}}\n]}}\n\"\"\"\n\n# Executor: simple for-loop\ndef run_flat(steps: list[FlatStep], tool_registry: dict) -> list[str]:\n    results = []\n    for s in steps:\n        result = tool_registry[s.tool](**s.args)\n        results.append(result)\n    return results"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Best for:"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " 3\u20136 step tasks with a clear sequential structure. For example, 'search \u2192 filter \u2192 summarise \u2192 save' is naturally sequential and benefits from simplicity over structure."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "DAG (Directed Acyclic Graph)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Each node carries an explicit "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "depends_on"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " list. The executor groups nodes into topological waves and runs each wave in parallel. Prior results are interpolated via a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "{{result:T1}}"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " placeholder syntax:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "@dataclass\nclass DAGNode:\n    id: str\n    tool: str\n    args: dict[str, Any]\n    depends_on: list[str] = field(default_factory=list)\n    result: str | None = None\n\nDAG_PROMPT = \"\"\"\nReturn a JSON plan as a DAG of steps. Each step lists its dependencies by ID.\nSteps with no dependencies can run in parallel.\nGoal: {goal}\nTools: {tools}\n\nJSON format: {{\"nodes\": [\n  {{\"id\": \"T1\", \"tool\": \"...\", \"args\": {{...}}, \"depends_on\": []}},\n  {{\"id\": \"T2\", \"tool\": \"...\", \"args\": {{...}}, \"depends_on\": [\"T1\"]}}\n]}}\n\"\"\"\n\n# Executor: topological waves (reuses topological_waves from task-decomposition)\ndef run_dag(nodes: list[DAGNode], tool_registry: dict) -> dict[str, str]:\n    index  = {n.id: n for n in nodes}\n    in_deg = {n.id: len(n.depends_on) for n in nodes}\n    graph  = {n.id: [] for n in nodes}\n    for n in nodes:\n        for dep in n.depends_on:\n            graph[dep].append(n.id)\n\n    results: dict[str, str] = {}\n    done: set[str] = set()\n\n    while len(done) < len(nodes):\n        ready = [nid for nid, deg in in_deg.items() if deg == 0 and nid not in done]\n        for nid in ready:\n            node = index[nid]\n            # Interpolate prior results into args\n            args_str = json.dumps(node.args)\n            for dep in node.depends_on:\n                args_str = args_str.replace(f\"{{{{result:{dep}}}}}\", results[dep][:500])\n            node.result = tool_registry[node.tool](**json.loads(args_str))\n            results[nid] = node.result\n            done.add(nid)\n            for successor in graph[nid]:\n                in_deg[successor] -= 1\n    return results"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Best for:"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " tasks with independent parallel branches. A research task that needs to search three different sources simultaneously benefits from a DAG: nodes T1a, T1b, T1c all depend on nothing, run in parallel, and feed a synthesis node T2."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "State Machine"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "States correspond to execution phases; transitions are conditional on the outcome of each phase. The executor evaluates conditions at each transition. Unlike a DAG, a state machine can branch and retry:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from enum import Enum, auto\n\nclass State(Enum):\n    START        = auto()\n    SEARCHING    = auto()\n    BROADENING   = auto()\n    FILTERING    = auto()\n    WRITING      = auto()\n    DONE         = auto()\n    FAILED       = auto()\n\nTRANSITIONS = {\n    State.START:      [(\"always\", State.SEARCHING)],\n    State.SEARCHING:  [(\"results_found\", State.FILTERING),\n                       (\"no_results\",    State.BROADENING)],\n    State.BROADENING: [(\"results_found\", State.FILTERING),\n                       (\"no_results\",    State.FAILED)],\n    State.FILTERING:  [(\"always\", State.WRITING)],\n    State.WRITING:    [(\"always\", State.DONE)],\n}\n\ndef run_state_machine(\n    initial_state: State,\n    tool_registry: dict,\n    context: dict,\n) -> dict:\n    state = initial_state\n    while state not in (State.DONE, State.FAILED):\n        result = tool_registry[state.name.lower()](context)\n        context[state.name] = result\n        # Evaluate transitions\n        for condition, next_state in TRANSITIONS[state]:\n            if condition == \"always\" or context.get(condition):\n                state = next_state\n                break\n    return context"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Best for:"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " tasks with meaningful failure modes that require different recovery paths. A search task that should broaden its query on empty results is naturally modelled as a state machine. Avoid it for simple sequential tasks \u2014 the added complexity is not worth it."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Hierarchical (Phased) Plan"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Steps are grouped into named phases. Each phase is a flat list; phases execute sequentially. Re-planning can replace a future phase without touching completed phases:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "@dataclass\nclass PlanPhase:\n    name: str\n    steps: list[FlatStep]\n\n@dataclass\nclass HierarchicalPlan:\n    goal: str\n    phases: list[PlanPhase]\n\nHIERARCHICAL_PROMPT = \"\"\"\nOrganise the plan for this goal into named PHASES, each containing ordered steps.\nGoal: {goal}\nTools: {tools}\n\nJSON format:\n{{\"phases\": [\n  {{\"name\": \"Research\", \"steps\": [\n    {{\"index\": 1, \"tool\": \"...\", \"args\": {{...}}, \"rationale\": \"...\"}}\n  ]}},\n  {{\"name\": \"Write\", \"steps\": [...]}}\n]}}\n\"\"\"\n\ndef run_hierarchical(plan: HierarchicalPlan, tool_registry: dict) -> dict:\n    all_results = {}\n    for phase in plan.phases:\n        print(f\"Phase: {phase.name}\")\n        for step in phase.steps:\n            result = tool_registry[step.tool](**step.args)\n            all_results[step.index] = result\n    return all_results"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Best for:"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " long plans (8+ steps) where conceptual grouping aids human review, or where a re-planner might replace later phases based on early phase results."
          }
        ]
      },
